% S6: coroutine reader parked in read-key-byte while MAIN cycles 20ms
% coroutine-sleep timers.  Regression: the scheduler's real sleep could
% wake just before the earliest timer expired (poll timeout truncated to
% whole ms, or EINTR), fall through to load main while main was still
% LINKED IN THE TIMER LIST, and main's next sleep re-inserted the linked
% node -- timer-list cycle, infinite timer_list_insert walk, stdin never
% polled again (dead keyboard at 99% CPU).  The byte at t+2s lands far
% beyond the ~200ms pre-fix corruption window.
(lib/keys.trx) run
/done false def
/reader {
    (reader-start\n) print flush
    read-key-byte
    { (got-byte: ) print /integer-type cast = flush }
    { (got-eof\n) print flush }
    if-else
    /done true store
} def
{
    mark { reader } coroutine-launch pop
    { done not } { 20 coroutine-sleep } while
} with-raw-mode
(S6-done\n) print flush
quit
